    <Descriptive_Notes>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Ornamental tables meant to be used as accent pieces, especially in 19th-century parlors. They are often of a round or oval shape, are of a size and style allowing one or two people to sit at the table in chairs, and often displayed a lamp, books, framed photographs, and other items of interest. For tables that were made en suite and finished on all sides, intended to be placed in the center of a room, often rectangular but of various shapes, and not necessarily designed for seating with chairs, use "center tables."</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>English</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000000/VP</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000007121/Sheraton, Cabinet Dictionary (1970)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000047708/Christie's Online (2001-)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Término de época empleado en el siglo XIX para mesas decorativas pensadas para ser usadas como puntos de atención, especialmente en salones. Use "mesa de centro” para mesas, generalmente fabricadas en conjunto, destinadas a ser ubicadas en el centro de una habitación.</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>Spanish</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000131/CDBP-SNPC</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000051034/TAA database (2000-)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Historische benaming die in de 19e eeuw werd gebruikt voor decoratieve tafels, bedoeld om  als pronkstuk te dienen, met name in woonkamers. Gebruik 'huiskamertafels' voor tafels die meestal bijpassend aan het overige meubilair zijn gemaakt en zijn bedoeld om in het midden van een kamer te staan.</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>Dutch</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000205/AAT-Ned</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000113770/AAT-Ned (1994-)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>裝飾用桌子，主要用於西元十九世紀的大客廳中作為特色家具。通常為橢圓形，尺寸與風格可容使用者坐在桌前的椅子上，且常佈置有檯燈、書籍、裝框相片，以及其他有趣的物品。若是指成套製作且各邊均修飾精美，供放置於房間中央，通常為方形，但其設計未必適合搭配椅子就座者，則稱為「中央桌」。</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>Chinese (traditional)</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000250/AS-Academia Sinica</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
